(α) The word perdrullis originally meant ‘enemy'. This is proved, not only by its derivation from duellum and the prefix per which stamped it with an unfavourable¹ sense found also in perfidus periurus perdere perire perperam etc, but also by the testimony of antiquity⁹ and the many surviving traces³ of ancient usage. But as the word lrestr‘s lost its original wide meaning ‘stranger’ and cameto mean no more than ‘enemy'3 so by a like narrowing perduellis came to mean only ‘internal enemy', a traitor or enemy to his own country. The offence committed by such a person is perduellio, a term vclosely corresponding to our ‘high treason ³.
